The state plans to restore 5.1 million hectares of degraded forest land to achieve 10 per cent forest cover, Environment CS Judy Wakhungu has said.On Friday, she said the Kenya Forest Service has mapped out all the degraded sites.Action plan for forest cover&ldquo;Kenya was the first country in Africa to do a wall-to-wall mapping of forest resources in 2010,&rdquo; Wakhungu added.The CS said the Constitution requires Kenyans to respect the environment and sustain it for the benefit of the future generations.&ldquo;To achieve this, the state is obligated to work to achieve and maintain a tree cover of at least 10 per cent of land area,&rdquo; she said.The forest cover has risen from 6.99 per cent in 2010 to 7.44 per cent currently, Wakhungu said.She spoke at KFS headquarters in Karura during the 10th anniversary of the agency.Wakhungu said there are notable reforms undertaken in the forestry sector since the enactment of the Forests Act of 2005.&ldquo;The reforms were majorly informed by the Kenya Forest Master plan, which identifies four key areas, namely legislative, policy, institutional and programme,&rdquo; she said.Sustainable use of resourcesThe CS said the ministry recognises the great role forests play in supporting productive sectors of the economy, and also how forestry practices and conservation efforts carried out by KFS and stakeholders play a major role in development of industries in rural areas.She said 300,000 people are employed in the timber and wood conversion sector.&ldquo;The timber industry in particular has greatly supported the construction and furniture sector, which is currently registering growth,&rdquo; Wakhungu said.She said every Kenyan citizen has a duty to cooperate with state organs to protect and conserve the environment and ensure ecologically sustainable development and use of natural resources.